
[1]rhetoric

   RHET'ORIC, n. [Gr. from to speak, to flow. Eng. to read. The primary
   sense is to drive or send. See Read.]

   1. The art of speaking with propriety, elegance and force.

   2. The power of persuasion or attraction; that which allures or charms.
   We speak of the rhetoric of the tongue, and the rhetoric of the heart
   or eyes.

   Sweet silent rhetoric of persuading eyes.
